<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-140-100 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 027 974</DOCID><JOURNAL>IBM System User  June 1991 v12 n6 p45(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Behind the Ace plan to hijack the desktop. (includes relatedarticle describing the ACE consortium)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Advanced Computing Environment (ACE) is a consortium of 21hardware and software vendors who want to create an open systemsdesktop environment which will support most of the currentmicrocomputer architecture, and will also utilize newtechnologies, mainly reduced instruction set computing (RISC) andUnix.andP;  Compaq is the company that started Ace, because it isconcerned that it has no RISC based workstation and that it willlose sales to suppliers of low-cost RISC based workstations.andO;Compaq and IBM have been losing microcomputer sales recently dueto a stale microcomputer market, and the lower priced clonemodels.andP;  Market analysts such as IDC believe that the ACEinitiative is the first step in the development for networked,distributed desktop computing.andP;  However, it believes that problemscould develop, especially since ACE is a consortium and requiresthe cooperation of many different companies.andP;  Users planning topurchase a microcomputer should forget about ACE for the timebeing because the creation of ACE was not prompted by customerdemand, key features of ACE are not deliverable and the technologyin ACE is open, built on commodity components and fairlycompatible with current microcomputer-Windows technology.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Advanced Computing EnvironmentConsortiaOpen SystemsMicrocomputersReduced-Instruction-Set ComputersUNIXVendors.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   What is Ace? (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>